{
  "comment_text": {
    "iti89:4.4": "Commentary gives <i lang='pi' translate='no'>me sutaṁ</i> as variant here. But this construction is found in a number places with <i lang='pi' translate='no'>vissuta</i>. See <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn86/en/sujato#18.40'>MN 86:18.40</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/thag16.8/en/sujato#15.2'>Thag 16.8:15.2</a>. ",
    "iti89:5.3": "Despite its fame, this, together with its parallel at <a href='https://suttacentral.net/pli-tv-kd17/en/sujato#4.8.11'>Kd 17:4.8.11</a>, is the only mention of Avīci hell in early Buddhism. It became a standard hell in later texts of the Buddhists (eg. <a href='https://suttacentral.net/kv23.3/en/sujato#1.10'>Kv 23.3:1.10</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/vb3/en/sujato#23.4'>Vb 3:23.4</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/cnd23/en/sujato#44.3'>Cnd 23:44.3</a>) and Brahmans (eg. Bhāgavata Purāṇa 5.26.28). The commentary explains <i lang='pi' translate='no'>avīci</i> as “without interval”, i.e. “unrelenting”; a similar explanation is cited by Vasubandhu at Abhidharmakośabhāṣya 3.58. ",
    "iti89:5.4": "Compare the description of hell as “four-doored” at <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn129/en/sujato#16.3'>MN 129:16.3</a> = <a href='https://suttacentral.net/mn130/en/sujato#16.3'>MN 130:16.3</a> = <a href='https://suttacentral.net/an3.36/en/sujato#16.1'>AN 3.36:16.1</a>. "
  },
